The Shared Responsibility Model.

The boundary between A-W-S's responsibility and the customer's is the most-quoted security framing on the platform, and most architecture decisions live on top of it.

A-W-S is responsible for security of the cloud, the physical data centres, the hardware, the hypervisor, the global network, and the managed-service control planes. The customer is responsible for security in the cloud, the data, identity, application code, and however they configure the services they use.

The line shifts depending on the service type. As you move from infrastructure-as-a-service toward serverless, A-W-S takes on more of the stack. On E-C-2 you own the operating-system patching, the runtime, the security group, and your data and I-A-M. On R-D-S, A-W-S takes over the operating system and database patching, but you still own the security group, the data, and the I-A-M. On S3 and Lambda, A-W-S handles almost everything up to the runtime, and you're left with your data, your policies, and your configuration.

Here's the key: the last row never moves. The customer is always responsible for their data, their I-A-M configuration, and their access controls, no matter how managed the service is. That's exactly why every service in this module is something you configure and you watch.
